{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/00340580953/1948070201/0024.xml":{"full_text":"r\nt COUNTY LABOR NEWS\nPMi'hnl Etny FAUy hj\nt^ie sijMMiT couiffr'twn, ip:\\ys\nA Non-Partisan Newspaper published in the best interests of-*\nOrganised Labor and the entire Community.\nEditorial, Advertising and Printing Offices\n920 SOUTH HIGH STREET Telephone FR-5,155\n-.'s i AKRON 11, OHIO 1\nEIGENMACHT-Editor and Publisher\n1 HJT' my\nEntered as Second Class Matter May 4, 1923, at Post'Office at\nAkron, Ohio, under the Act of March 3, 1897 -f\n\ntl l\nYearly Subscription in Advance__L_!___!\u2019_I__$3.00\nNews of interest from the various local unions under the jurisdiction of the\nCongress of Industrial Organizations, Akron Industrial Union Council and the\nAmerican Federation of Labor and the Trades and Labor Assembly is solicited.\nAll news matter should reach the editorial office of the Summit County Labor\nNews not later than Tuesday.\nThe Summit County Labor News accepts advertisements from firms not\non'the'unfair list of the Central Bodies.^ It must be umlsritopd, however, tha\u00a7\nAs editorial policy of thid-publication is affected in no way by\u201d suc^ advertise\nments. t ti vV tv- v\nOhio\u2019s Compensation Shame Glow\u2019s t\nOhio\u2019s unemployment cohlpensationBhame is growing more\ndisgraceful month bymojitb. ;VV\u2018\ni>.\u00ab This brutal fact was proven by the publication of figures com\npiled by1 the'Federal Security Agency.oftheSbcial Secilmy Ad\nministration.\nThese figures show that Ohm\u2019s disqualification ratio, for all\nreasons; now stands at 24.4\u2014^the highest in the nation.\nBecause of the completely unrealistic yardstick used ip Ohio\nto determine the eligibility of an applicant nearly 25 of every\n100 applicants is refused aid.\nThis compares with a national rate of six out of every hundred\nand of New York state where less than three out of every 100 are\nturned down.\n\u2022V Revealing the basic infamy of the Ohio law\u2014which carries no\nhumane definition of \u201csuitable work\u201d\u2014is this fact: The Ohio dis\n1 qualification rate, which w;as down to 15.1 in the first three months\nof 1947 had climbed to its present level 24.4, by the end of the\n\"\u2018year\u2014the latest period for which figures are available.\nThe completely technical reports of the Federal Security\nAgenc^ are dry as dust as far as the average reader is. concerned.\nBut intepreted, they reveal a cold-blooded inhumane situation.\nThis situation eannot, in all fairness, be charged to the Bureau\nof Unemployment Compensation'as such.\nAdmittedly some of the .personnel consider themselves as\ntraffic cops\u2014out to deny compensation to every applicant for the\nthost obscure reason.\nBut in the huge majority of the cases the only blame must\nfall on the law itself and the Ohio Legislature which has continu\nally passed amendments to make this law tougher,\nv \u201cFigures don\u2019t iie. That\u2019s an old adage that is sometimes not\n.true. But it is too sadly true in this instance,\u201d said Jack Kroli,\nPresident of the Ohio CIO Council, as he examined the. chart repro\nduCed with this story.\n\u201cWe have vigorously criticised this law in the past. We have\nstruggled for a long time in the Ohio Legislature to get thus,\nwicked law changed. These figures fully justify our stand. They\nfully justify our criticisms and our struggles. They show that the\nsituation has not changed for the better. In fact, it is growing\nworse.\n\u201cThis is a mest important problem and it will surely grow in\nimportance when this country suffers a recession. The present\nsetup definitely means that a recession would upset our entire\neconomy here in Ohio.\n\u201cUnemployment compensation was meant to be a \u2018cushion\u2019 for\nour economy in bad times. The way the law is now drawn up, our\nworkers would find no cushion when the bottom drops out from\nUnder. Instead the worker would find just plain hard rock.\n\u201cUntil we get a liberal Legislature and state administration\nip Ohio, we will continue to have these outrageous statistics.\n\u201cBut when the next Legislature convenes the Ohio CIO\nCouncil will be back in the arena fighting\u2014back fighting the\nsame old battle.\u201d\n\u25a0Or\nWho Paid for the Payroll Ta$ Lie??\nBehind the drive for the payroll tax in Columbus is this, story\nof one of the most amazing and most expensive political cam\npaiffns ever staged op a municipal issue.\nThe wheels began to roll as soon as the city council voted to\nput the' issue to the voters at a special election, ignoring the $20,\n000 of taxpayers\u2019 money that would be wasted by passing up, the\nprimary election. H j T\nByer and Bowan, Columbus\u2019 top advertising firm, was hired*\nto put the tax across, Ho one knows who. hired'the firm, ho\\y\nmuch it was paid, or where the money came from. City officials\nconsistently ignored all questions on this subject.\nThis firm then outlined an extensive and expensive campaign.\nEvery medium was used\u2014newspapers, radio, posters, advertise\nments and pamphlets.\nAs soon as the primary election was out of the way, all three\nColumbus newspapers launched a terroristic campaign designed to\n'\u201cscare\u201d the voters into approving the tax.\nAll news releases submitted by those opposing the tux were\nrejected or buried alongside the want ads. Yet every release by\nproponents of the tax received big headlines on page one.\nThe newspapers either discontinued, or sharply curtailed\ntheir \u201cletters to the editor\u201d column, so that opponents could hot\nuse that means. 1\nReporters were assigned to write serial stories, which empha\nsized terror, claiming that defeat of the tax would mean chaos for\nthe city. And one newspaper, the Columbus Dispatch, continually\npublished this statement: VCIO is conducting a malicious whisper\ning campaign against the ordinance\u2019 1\nThe exact truth of the matter was:\n1\u2014 CIO\u2019s attempts to get items in this paper were unsuccess\nful. i. i. 1 v .iiiii\n2\u2014CIO was using every means at its command to get its op*\nv, position i? tpe tnx ucrotp iq the public.\nAh out-of-town newspaperman,i aligned to do a story op the\nColumbus tax fight, commented that the newspaper campaign in\nColumbus was \u201cThe most amazingly, unethical journalistic cam\npaign I have ever witnessed. s\nRadio stations, forced by FCC regulations to be impartial,\nsold.time to both sides and also, made a small amount of fice radio\ntime available. 4\nBut the edge in the fight went to the city administration,\nwhich threw every agency into the fight. Here\u2019s how the auhiin\nistration operated:\n1\u2014Officials deliberately ordered violations of civil service\nV f regulations and made it<a \u201cmust\u201d for every city Worker\n.to do his part to put the tax across.\n2- r-Uoiformed policemen and firemen handed out pro-payroll\ntax literature during their regular working hours.\n3\u2014 CUy hall employes were pressed into the task of address-\ntag thousands of pieces of literature.\n4- sSehooln were used ln the propaganda campaign, with\nSafe Driving Is\nr Fourth\nJrive safely\nid be alive after the\nFtttirth of-\u25a0 July weekend was the ap\npeal made today to Ohio motorists by\nEarl L. Reeb, \"Director of the Ohio\nDepartment of Highways.\n'\u2019Although- fireworks' no longer con\nstitute the chi|f hazard, Director Reel)\npointed out that the Fourth is still the\nmost dangerous day of the year be\nOguSf pf traffic* accident^ and dSown\nil\u00bbg8.: V:-V\nAi)d traffic; accidents, he reminded,\nare\u2019 by far a\u2019greater hazard than\ndrownings.\nAs part of Qovernor Thomas J.\nHerbert\u2019s state-wide program of traf\nfic safety, the State Highway Depart\nment\u2019s Division of Traffic and'Safety\nurged motorists to celebrate the\nFourth by taking it easy in traffic\nand being on the alert for other driv\nen who are not* smart enough to be\ncareful.. ,5\nThe Division of Traffic and Safety\nparticularly urged motorists to:\n1\u2014 Adjnst speed to the condition of 1\nthe' road,weather, traffic, your\ncar and yourself.\n2\u2014 ^Po' your slowing down before\nreaching curves7 and intersec\ntions. s.l sh\n3\u2014 At night dfive so that you can\nstu* within the clear, illuminated\n4i**ance ahead.\nOhio PAC To\niio CIO-Political Action Commit\ntee will launch its Tall election Cam\npaign with a state-wide rally in Cin\ncinnati on August <8, Chairman Jack\nKroll and Secretary-Treasurer Wil\nliam Lavelle revealed today in a joint\nannouncement^\nLashing out at the record of both\nthe 80th Congress and the 97th Ohio\nGeneral Assembly, they said the PAC\nkick-off rally Will' be held, in' the\nNetherlapd Plaza Hotel at Cincinnati,\nIn announcing the rally, Kroll and\nLavelle called for representation from\nevery Local Union, Council, and PAC,\nUnit at the meeting, at which a speak\ner of national prominence will be\nheard.\nScheduled for consideration at this\nsession will be the Ohio CIO-PAC\u2019s\nstate legislative program.'\nDenouncing both the Congress and\nthe state legislature for coldly disre\ngarding the needs of the people in\nI their desire to do the bidding the sel\nfish-vested interests, the PAC offi\ncials observed:\u2014\n\u201cThese are grave and important\ndays in the history of our country\nand for the Labor Movement, tdo.' We\nmust recognize the heavy responsi\nbility resting upori Us to preserve\ndemocratic institutions which are\nthreatened not only on' the interna\nschool children being compelled to take pamphlets home\nto their parents.\n5-\u20140n' flection day, city functions ground to a standstill, as\nemployes were used in a giant \u201cget-put-the-votd\u201d dHve.\n\u00bb\u2014\u2018City employees were asked to \u2666\u2018voluntarily\u201d contribute\nmoney to the campaign and those who didn\u2019t were told\nthey wpuldbe \u201clooked upon as one Who failed in team wt>rk\nby definite lack of interest.\u201d f\nIn the face of this campaign, William Spratley, president of\nthe Columbus CIQ Council, told reporters, \u201cit is amazing that\nthere were so many \u2018against\u2019 votes cast.\u201d\nSince Columbus was an experimental laboratory, in which\nways of promoting the tax were tested for other cities, it was ap\nparent that the same technique will be repeated everywhere that\nthe tax comes up for a vote.\ntional fron.t, but are seriously endan\ngered on the domestic scene by.\nmonopoly,- anti-Unionism, extortionate\nt. t..;/ y.-i-.i.. .\u00abv?f\nBuy Sayings Bonds\ni r V A 1 rTT\nIn line with the policy of the AFL,\nPhil Hdtinah, secretary-treasurer of\nthe'Ohio State Federation of Labor,\nis calling ittention^to Security Loan\nWeek in Ohio this week*\n\u201cThe safest investment for Amer\nican workers is fc\u2019ii Savings Bonds,\u201d\nHannah asserted. He called special\nattention to Sejries F fnd G B^nds as\ninvestments for union funds.' Only\nindividuals can invest in Series E\nBonds but F and G Savings Bonds\ncan be purchased by any organization\nor association. Many AFL unions\nhare invested unto* funds in Series F\nan^' G Bonds' and are continuing to do\nso/ Unions who have funds to invest\nin these bonds are urged to invest\nbefore duly 15th in order that 'the\naniount purchased may count in' the\nSecurity Loan Campaign' goals.\nSeries F Bonds are 12 year appre\nciation bonds available to individuals,\ntrustees, partnerships, associations\nand corporations,; They are registered\nand tion-transferable, and bear inter\nest at thi; rate of 2.53 per cent a year,\ncompounded seini-annually, .when\nbonds are held to maturity.\nSeries G Bonds are current income\nbonds issued at face value: They\nI bear interest at the rate of 2V4 per\ncent per annum, payable semi-annual\nly by Treasury check, every six\nmonths as lohg as the bond is held, or\nuntil maturity, which is 12 years from\nthe date of purchase.\nSeries G Bonds are issued on $100,\n$500, $1000, $5000 and $10,000 de-.\nnominations. Series F is offered in'\nthe same denomination and includes a\n$25 bond.\nTotal employment is expected to ex\nceed 60,000,000 jobs this summer.\nPoH Against\nTvH Groms\nAs; more and more ballots are\ncounted in the AFL poll of its mem\nbers\u2019 attitude towards the Taft-Hart\nley law the margin against the union\nbaiting act increases. The ten-to-one\ndecision of the rank and file of organ\nized labor against the act; revealed in\nthe April count has risen tji> ioto one,\nthe AFL announced recently.\n\u00a3$j> far $S$L7 votes against'the act\nhave beeh received in' AfL headquar\nter^ as against^ only 2, l6j for it.\nAnti-labor commentators, who didn\u2019t\ntake the trouble to find.out how' the\nPoll i\u00bb being conducted,\" have attacked\nit as an insufficient test of labor\nsentiment. But,' as the' AFL points\nout,' ballots were not sent 'to each\nmember. They have been printed in\nAFL papers, whose readers are asked\nto clip them qnd mailj them m. No\nhuge vote Was 'anticipated, but the\nAFL is sure an adequate sample has\nbeen obtained. \u20195' 1\u2018\"\nIn the one case Where ballots were\nprinted in bulk and distributed at lo^\ncal union meetings\u2014oh the request of\n\u25a0the International. Molders and Foun\ndry Workers Union\u2014the result was a\n5,264 to 76 vote against Taft-Hartley.\nThe AFL points out too that in an\nother' \u201cpoll\u201d on' the' act, the union\nshop authorization ballots conducted\nby, the. NLRB union groups have in\nover 98 per cent of the elections voic\ned their confidence in their organiza\ntions. Taft-Hqrtley\u2019s sponsors claim\ned, when the,law was being considered\nin Congress, that union members\nwould show in these elections their dis-,\ntrust Of \u201ctrade union bureaucrats.\u201d\nMeet* July, J9\nThe next meeting of the Compen\nsation Committee of Akron CIO\nCouncil will be held in the Council\u2019s\noffices, 672 South Main street? on\nJuly 19th. An appeal is being made\nfor each local affiliated with the\nvotatePuhlic\nRelations Plan\nThe AFL announced recently that it\nis embarking upon an extensive'pub\nlic relations v\nlie relations program \u2019to promote a\nmoire widisprdad underStandfitii of the\naims, programs\nAFL.\u201d\nand\nideals of the\nt\n\u2022Reporting upon a degigiqp made at\nthe recent Milwaukee' meeting of the\nAFL executive council, President Wil\nliam'Green said. \u201cToday, more, than\n'ever before, it is \u2019essential that la\nbor\u2019s point of view and labpr\u2019p stake\nin our way of life sTioutd^ made\nclear to Americans everywhere\u2014\n(forcefully, honestly andwitliout dis\ntortion. In the past, withput a formal\npublic-relations program to. do *just\nthat, Tabor's side of. the picture has\nnot always been either fully or sym\npathetically covered.\u201d\nThe public-relations fjrm., of, Owen\nand Chappel, Inc., New York, has\nbeen hired to carry out the AFL pro\ngram,' and Prefsidfnt Green has assert\ned: \u201cWe intend to keep on with our\nefforts until our objectives are' at\ntained.\u201d*\ninside the AFL, the most persistent\nadvocate of planned' public-relations\nactivity has been Julius Hochman,\nvice president of the International\nLadies Garment Workers\u2019 flnion, who'\nseveral times brought the idea before\nAFL conventions.\nThe American'Federation of Musi\ncians-AFL, and the United'1 Mine\nWorkers-unaffiliated have recently\ninaugurated similar programs. Re\nsults of the AFM program, which has\nbeen in effect several months, played\na part in \u201cselling\u201d the idea to the\nAFL.\nCouncil to send representatives to the\nmeeting.\nVarious questions of interest to\nthe compensation committees of the\nlocals will be discussed at the session.\nCome In to Carlton's tomorrow\nJRd ife, what Clothing miracles\n\ncan\nr t h\nat thls stfre\n\nMen, meet the Suit Buys of the. Year Carltpn\u2019s All\nWool Hard-Finish Worsteds and Sharkskins! It\u2019s fair to\nCOM^ARh:, and it\u2019s eas